COMMENTS: visited vs. referenced here might need to be looked at, since this whole section is kind of a flashback/history contextualization. Also, confirm whether city/town/whatever tag is needed

case study because this could either refer to dardanus (city) or the dardanoi tribe, and I can't really figure out which. Definitely needs to be looked through, Dardanian tag adjusted to whatever it actually is, and region or city/town and referenced tags added as necessary|The only argument I can think of is that it refers to Dardanus (city) because Timasion took the place of Clearchus, who was an exiled Spartan, but lived in the Troas region, and immediately after they put Xanthicles the Achaean in charge of what was formerly Socrates the Achaeans position, so perhaps they could be trying to keep similar ethnic/geographically associated leaders in charge of similar regiments?|The same ethnic replacement is made with Cleanor the Arcadian succeeding Agias the Arcadian, but the appointment immediately after is Philesus the Achaean succeeding Menon of Thessaly, so it's not strong evidence.|Update: looked at the Greek and it's Dardanus the city because the Greek is Δαρδανεύς which is the demonym of the city, whereas the tribe uses Δαρδάνιοι, Δάρδανοι. It would seem to me that the English form should be closer to Dardaneusian than Dardanian, but hey I'm not an etymologist
case study reasons laid out in book 2
Δία ξένιον in Greek, so annotated as such.

as with book 2, needs further research to figure out which one this is|Ok, so after chasing a fair amount of rabbit holes, I think that if this Mithradates was to be anyone found elsewhere in the historical record, it would Mithradates, Satrap of Cappadocia. The Greek in this section and later in 7.8.25, when the satrap is mentioned, is the same (Μιθραδάτης). Mithradates of Cius, mentioned in Xenophon's Cyropaedia (who also might be the same person as Mithradates II of Cius(??) who is mentioned by Diodorus) has a one-letter difference (Μιθριδάτης). This is absolutely not strong evidence on its own, and I think it's entirely plausible the letter was changed when the name was Latinized (or it's a mispelling). However, if Mithradates of Cius and Mithradates II of Cius are the same person, than it's extremely unlikely he is this Mithradates, as Lucian of Samosata gives Mithradates II of Cius' age at death as 84 in what is now 302 BCE, which means he wouldn't have even been born by the time the Anabasis takes place, and Lucian would have to be off by ~30 years or so for it to line up.  Due to the lack of decisive evidence, however, I won't be linking Satrap Mithradates' wikipedia entry to this annotation and will leave it blank.

The Greek uses “ἄνδρες Ἕλληνες” so the translation “Men of Greece” doesn’t as clearly capture that it’s an adjective ethnic identifier in the original text. Given that “Greek men” is just as reasonable a translation, I annotated it as collective.ethnic

Case study because it seems to be the Nimrud river, but need to look into further to confirm|Ok so the river actually appears to be the Zabas Megas/Great Zab, though possibly a smaller tributary. The Zabas Mega is the same river that flowed by Nimrud, has tributaries in the general area where Xenophon is, and meets the Tigris nearby too.

Xenophon writes that the city that used to be Median but was already deserted in his time, so it's not looking good for the archaeologists out there. Case study and ambiguous, a proper lost city. Not any of the Larisa cities listed on wikipedia; hopefully mapping will reveal more of its location|Also maybe give it a .abandoned tag, since it was abandoned even in Xenophon's time?|This needs to be verified since i couldn't find any actual academic sources backing this up, but someone said Larisa is actually modern day Kalhu/Nimrud|The Nimrud explanation does seem decently plausible judging the Zapatas river to be the Great Zab.  Also Pleiades has a gazetteer stating as much

Same boat as Larisa. Maybe give it an abandoned tag. I need to verify if this is actually backed up academically, but Mespila seems to be identified with modern day Nineveh. The locations seem to line up at first glance|Pleiades also supports the idea that Mespila is Mosul/Nineveh.
